{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":10174,"record_hash":"sha256:c011c7ed712915efbe0dd553700dd861650907048d63770580412f918b6ca9c8","timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:50:05.169Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 1ebaa7\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 2194\nOutput:\n# Agent Session Handoff Design\n\nThis note sketches the handoff feature that sits above the `but-agentlog`\nprimitives. It is intentionally not an implementation contract yet.\n\n## Goal\n\nLet a developer continue work from one machine, agent, or provider session in\nanother machine, agent, or provider session.\n\nThe target experience:\n\n1. work happens on a branch with agentlog capture enabled\n2. GitMeta sync moves captured agentlog data with the repository metadata\n3. another machine checks out or switches to the branch\n4. the user asks an agent to catch up\n5. the agent uses GitButler commands to discover and read relevant prior session\n   context\n6. the new agent continues with enough context to be useful, without pretending\n   it has natively resumed the old provider session\n\nThis is contextual handoff, not exact provider-native replay.\n\n## Current Building Blocks\n\nThe primitive layer can already provide the facts a handoff flow needs:\n\n- durable project-scoped sessions\n- capture turns within sessions\n- ordered transcript records within each turn\n- environment observations for each turn\n- GitMeta sync of the stored data\n- verified lookup of sessions related to a branch, review, or change\n- bounded hydration of related turn windows\n\nThat is enough to design an agent-facing workflow without adding product-shaped\nstate to `but-agentlog`.\n\n## Design Bias\n\nThe agent should get tools, not a generated handoff essay.\n\nThat said, raw transcript access alone is not enough. Once sessions include\nsubagents, compactions, large backfills, and repeated captures, asking the next\nagent to infer everything from a giant transcript is brittle and expensive.\n\nThe useful middle ground is:\n\n- deterministic orientation commands\n- bounded transcript hydration\n- stable machine-readable JSON\n- enough metadata to let the agent choose what to read next\n- optional human-readable output for manual debugging\n\nDo not bake a model-generated\n[TRUNCATED]\n <session-key> --turn <turn-key> [--from start|end|<index>] [--limit N]\n```\n\nThis is enough for an agent to:\n\n1. discover prior sessions\n2. orient itself in the session and turn structure\n3. read bounded transcript records only where needed\n\nThere should not be a first-class `handoff` command. Handoff is the workflow the\nagent performs with these tools.\n\nIf `branch` is provided without a branch name, it should mean the current branch.\nThat keeps the common prompt easy:\n\n```text\nCheck whether there are prior agent sessions related to this branch and catch up.\n```\n\nThe CLI can keep storage terms like `session_key` and `turn_key` internally, but\nhuman-facing help should prefer `session id` and `turn id`. \"Key\" reads like an\nimplementation detail.\n\n### `sessions`\n\nPurpose: answer \"what sessions should I inspect?\"\n\nTargeted form:\n\n```text\nbut agentlog sessions branch agentlog-turn-storage\n```\n\nUntargeted form:\n\n```text\nbut agentlog sessions --limit 10\n```\n\nThe targeted form returns sessions related to a branch, review, or change. The\nuntargeted form returns recent project sessions. Both should return compact\norientation data.\n\nJSON should include:\n\n- requested target, if any\n- `session_key`\n- `updated_at`\n- `started_at`, if known\n- `turn_count`\n- `record_count`\n- `related_turn_keys`, only for targeted lookup\n- match evidence, not confidence:\n  - `matched_by`, for example `branch_observed`, `review_observed`,\n    `change_observed`, or `explicit_reference`\n  - `matched_turn_keys`\n  - other observed branch/review/change keys, when present\n- source metadata: agents, providers, models, tool versions\n- latest turn key and latest capture timestamp\n- latest user/assistant excerpts, when cheap to derive\n\nThis command should not hydrate transcript records. It is an index card.\nIt should be sorted by most recent activity first.\n\n### `timeline`\n\nPurpose: answer \"what happened across this session, and which turns look worth\nreading?\"\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nbut agentlog timeline sha256-9d942495afce65d863ef4d05e61ce2da --limit 20\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:50:05.169Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}